\begin_layout Standard
1) For instance, consider the case of the Great Recession where cutting
 the interest rates did not really have the desired effect.
 This was due to the fact that excess capacity was more of a problem than
 aggregate demand and as a result cutting interest rates even further barely
 stimulated aggregate demand and did not lead to a recovery due to the fact
 that excess capacity was a bigger issue in the economy.
 It could be argued that instead of focusing on interest rates, debt restructuri
ng may be an effective way of restoring aggregate demand.
 If households are credit constrained then changing interest rates matters
 less than freeing the consumers of the debt that is preventing them from
 being able to spend.
 As well, if liquidity is concentrated in those that have a lower marginal
 propensity to consume.
