\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

4) The fiscal multiplier is small if the marginal utility of consumption
 is close to constant or there is a highly increasing marginal disutility
 of producing output.
 The fiscal multiplier can be high if we are near the zero-lower bound,
 we have componetarity between public and private investmnent, the curvative
 of our utility function is large, or if we have consumption-labor complementari
ty.
 Interestingly, if the government spends the money on completely useless
 things that people would not normally buy then the multiplier is higher,
 but if the government spends the money on things that people would otherwise
 normally buy like healthcare or education, then the multiplier is smaller.
 
