The main differences in the assumptions between the two strands of New Keynesian
 models deal with the types of rigidites.
 While the former set of New Keynesian models focus on nominal rigidities,
 the latter set of New Keynesian models focus more on real rigidities such
 as markets not clearing due to imperfect information.
 As well, the former set of New Keynesian models focus on exogenous demand
 shocks, whereas the latter set focus on endogenous demand shocks.
 To see which is more relevant we can see how well they predict large downturns
 and match empirical data.
