A balance sheet recession occurs when high indebtedness causes individuals
 and firms to collectively focus on paying down debt instead of focusing
 on spending or investing, causing economic growth to decline.
 In traditional models these play no effect because the balance sheet of
 the firm is not considered an endogenous variable in the firms optimizing
 behavior since they only consider nominal rigidities and not real rigidities
 such as dealing with risk averse firms facing the possibility of bankruptcy.
 The Great Recession involved more than just balance sheet effects since
 the net worth had real effects on the macroeconomic variables.
 The shocks got amplified and had persistent effects, causing the balance
 sheet effects to have a real impact on the economy.
